Float requires 32 bits of memory the double 64 bits of memory.  Since double is the default real number format, the
"d" or "D" suffixes are option in a variable declaration.  If need be use the "d" and "D" suffixes for clarity.  In
the case of a float use "f" or "F" because you are restricting the real number format compared to a double.

One can assign an integer literal to a float or double variable, Java will do the casting for you.  Since double is the
default real number data type, assigning a real number literal to a float variable will produce an error if the
literal is not suffixed with an "f" or "F" as a double would be assigned to a float yielding a "lossy conversion".

Actually modern day computers have functionality built in at the chip level to deal with a double number faster
than a float number, my guess is because double numbers are so much more in demand (greater precision).